Let  $$A = \left( {\matrix{
   1 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   2 &amp; 1 &amp; { - 3}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right).$$ and $$10$$ $$B = \left( {\matrix{
   4 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   { - 5} &amp; 0 &amp; \alpha   \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 2} &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right)$$. if $$B$$ is 
<p>the inverse of matrix $$A$$, then $$\alpha $$ is</p>

questions.explanation:
Given that $$10B$$ $$\,\,\, = \left[ {\matrix{
   4 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   { - 5} &amp; 0 &amp; \alpha   \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 2} &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right]$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow B = {1 \over {10}}\left[ {\matrix{
   4 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   { - 5} &amp; 0 &amp; \alpha   \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 2} &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right]$$
<br><br>Also since, $$B = {A^{ - 1}} \Rightarrow AB = I$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {1 \over {10}}\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   2 &amp; 1 &amp; { - 3}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]\left[ {\matrix{
   4 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   { - 5} &amp; 0 &amp; \alpha   \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 2} &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right] = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$ 
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {1 \over {10}}\left[ {\matrix{
   {10} &amp; 0 &amp; {5 - 2}  \cr 
   0 &amp; {10} &amp; { - 5 + \alpha }  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; {5 + \alpha }  \cr 

 } } \right] = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {{5 - \alpha } \over {10}} = 0$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \alpha  = 5$$

questions.content:
Let $$A = \left( {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right)$$. The only correct
<p>statement about the matrix $$A$$ is</p>

questions.explanation:
$$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$
<br><br>clearly $$\,\,\,A \ne 0.\,$$ Also $$\,\,\left| A \right| =  - 1 \ne 0$$
<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $${A^{ - 1}}\,\,$$ exists, further 
<br><br>$$\left( { - 1} \right)I = \left[ {\matrix{
   { - 1} &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right] \ne A$$
<br><br>Also $${A^2} = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]\left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$
<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right] = I$$

